You know   my theory: Every bad thing that a public company does is=C2=A0al=
so=C2=A0securities fraud. If there is a data breach=C2=A0or sexual harassme=
nt or animal mistreatment or pollution at a company,=C2=A0and the public fi=
nds out about it and the stock goes down, then someone will sue the company=
, arguing that it defrauded shareholders by leading them to believe that th=
ere=C2=A0wouldn=E2=80=99t be=C2=A0a data breach or sexual harassment or wha=
tever. And this theory is=C2=A0weird, and people sometimes say =E2=80=9Cwai=
t shouldn=E2=80=99t securities fraud be for, like, accounting misstatements=
, not sexual harassment?=E2=80=9D But it is a little hard to articulate a l=
imiting principle. If a company convinces investors that it is good, but it=
 is in fact bad, then it has defrauded them, and badness is not limited to =
accounting.
Once you have mastered this basic idea, you can apply it to other laws. For=
 instance, every bad thing that a company does is=C2=A0also=C2=A0bank fraud=
, if the company has ever borrowed money from a bank. The  Wall Street Jour=
nal reports:

The U.S. government is looking into whether Amazon.com Inc. might have misl=
ed lenders about its workplace safety record to obtain credit, using a law =
stemming from the savings-and-loan crisis in a legal move a lawyer for the =
company called =E2=80=9Cunprecedented.=E2=80=9D
The Manhattan U.S. Attorney=E2=80=99s Office is conducting an investigation=
 into Amazon under the Financial Institutions Reform, Recovery and Enforcem=
ent Act, a law that allows civil cases to be brought over wrongdoing that i=
mpacts banks. The office has deployed the 1989 law at the same time the Lab=
or Department presses a workplace safety investigation of Amazon that has a=
lready led to several citations. =E2=80=A6
The U.S. Attorney=E2=80=99s Office in Manhattan issued a subpoena in August=
 to Amazon for information the company might have shared with financial ins=
titutions involved in at least $90 million in contracts or agreements with =
the online retailer in the previous five years, specifically information it=
 shared on its injury rates and labor law compliance. =E2=80=A6
=E2=80=9CIt is difficult to understand how a safety inquiry could plausibly=
 be shoehorned into a Firrea investigation,=E2=80=9D Zainab Ahmad, a partne=
r at outside counsel Gibson, Dunn & Crutcher LLP, wrote in a letter to gove=
rnment lawyers that is included with court papers.
=E2=80=9CFirrea addresses financial fraud, not employee safety,=E2=80=9D Ms=
. Ahmad added, calling the U.S. Attorney=E2=80=99s Office=E2=80=99s legal t=
heory =E2=80=9Cextremely tenuous=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=9Cunprecedented.=E2=80=
=9D=C2=A0

It is very easy to understand how a safety inquiry could plausibly be shoeh=
orned into a Firrea investigation!=C2=A0Ahmad doesn=E2=80=99t like it, and =
really neither do=C2=A0I, but I=C2=A0understand=C2=A0it.
Amazon has an equity market capitalization just shy of $1 trillion, tens of=
 billions of dollars per year of cash flow from operations, A1/AA credit ra=
tings=C2=A0and 5-year credit default swaps that trade inside of 50 basis po=
ints. If you are a bank and you loaned Amazon $90 million (!?) in the last =
five years, you are just fine with that decision. No bank has become insolv=
ent because it loaned money to Amazon and now Amazon is facing =E2=80=9Csev=
eral citations=E2=80=9D from the Labor Department.
But, sure! In its  credit agreement, Amazon says that it complies with the =
law, so if it did not comply with labor law then its credit agreement was n=
ot strictly true. And perhaps in the due diligence for a loan, a bank sent =
over a questionnaire asking things like =E2=80=9Care your workplaces safe,=
=E2=80=9D and probably Amazon answered =E2=80=9Cyes=E2=80=9D in some sort o=
f qualified and lawyered way, and if the answer should have been =E2=80=9Cn=
o=E2=80=9D then, right, fraud. Of course no one at a bank=C2=A0made a credi=
t decision=C2=A0based on that questionnaire. It=E2=80=99s not like Jamie Di=
mon was called in to decide whether JPMorgan Chase & Co. should lend to Ama=
zon, and he said =E2=80=9Chmm, I don=E2=80=99t know, how=E2=80=99s their sa=
fety record,=E2=80=9D and the analyst who sent the due diligence questionna=
ire was like =E2=80=9Cwell they say here that it=E2=80=99s good,=E2=80=9D a=
nd Dimon said =E2=80=9Cwell okay, if you think we can trust them about that=
, then let=E2=80=99s lend them the money,=E2=80=9D and JPMorgan went ahead =
on that basis and was shocked to find out that Amazon=E2=80=99s safety reco=
rd was not so good. Presumably what happened is that some credit committee =
made the credit decision by asking =E2=80=9Cwait this is Amazon?=E2=80=9D a=
nd the relationship banker was like =E2=80=9Cyep=E2=80=9D and the credit co=
mmittee was like =E2=80=9Csure wave it in=E2=80=9D and nobody discussed wor=
ker safety at all. And if they did, it was probably along the lines of =E2=
=80=9Cwell, Amazon is a huge company and a great credit, shame about its sp=
otty worker safety record but we gotta make this loan.=E2=80=9D
Oh, I am being a little glib. Sometimes banks consider not only the actual =
credit risk of a financing but also the reputational risk: Even if you thin=
k some major oil company is huge and stable and a great credit, you=E2=80=
=99ll probably have a contentious committee meeting about lending it money,=
 because there is activist pressure on banks not to lend to oil companies. =
(And, of course,  pressure the other way.)=C2=A0My impression is that lendi=
ng money to Amazon is not really in this category, but is it possible that =
the deal memo had a paragraph like =E2=80=9CReputational risk: A lot of peo=
ple don=E2=80=99t like how Amazon treats its workers=E2=80=9D? Is it possib=
le that the deal memo went on to say =E2=80=9CMitigating factor: Amazon say=
s its workplace safety is good=E2=80=9D? I mean, sure. Would its banks have=
 loaned it the money on the same terms no matter what Amazon said about its=
 workplace safety? Yes, I think so. But you can understand how the prosecut=
ors might be doing the shoehorning.
Elsewhere, and related, here is Patrick McKenzie on =E2=80=9CKYC and AML: b=
eyond the acronyms=E2=80=9D:

Many, many crimes involve lies, but most lies told are not crimes and most =
lies told are not recorded for forever. We did, however, make a special rul=
e for lies told=C2=A0to banks: they=E2=80=99re potentially very serious cri=
mes and they will be recorded with exacting precision, for years, by one of=
 the institutions in society most capable of keeping accurate records and m=
ost findable by agents of the state.
This means that if your crime touches money, and much crime is financially =
motivated, and you get beyond the threshold of crime which can be done pure=
ly offline and in cash, you will at some point attempt to interface with th=
e banking system. And you will lie to the banks, because you need bank acco=
unts, and you could not get accounts if you told the whole truth.
The government=C2=A0wants you to do this. Their first choice would be you n=
ot committing crimes, but contingent on you choosing to break the law, they=
=C2=A0prefer you also lie to a bank.

Same idea with workplace safety violations.

