   =20
      Mango
   =20
 =20

A lot of stuff happens in crypto markets that, if it happened in the stock =
market, would obviously be securities fraud. There is insider trading in cr=
ypto tokens. There is market manipulation. There are pump-and-dumps. All th=
e standard illegal stuff that happens in stock markets also happens in cryp=
to markets.
There is a fairly popular view=C2=A0in crypto that it is not illegal when i=
t happens in crypto, that crypto markets are governed by their own rules, t=
hat =E2=80=9Ccode is law,=E2=80=9D that if you do a thing that is not expli=
citly forbidden by the terms of the crypto platform you are using then no g=
overnment should have any authority to stop you. This is not the=C2=A0only=
=C2=A0view in crypto =E2=80=94=C2=A0a lot of people disagree =E2=80=94=C2=
=A0but it is=C2=A0a=C2=A0view. It is not, I think it is safe to say, the vi=
ew of US federal prosecutors. Their view is that this stuff is all just as =
illegal in crypto markets as it is in the stock market, that it is fraud,=
=C2=A0and that if it catches their attention they can and will bring crimin=
al cases. And so   they do.
This seems pretty simple for federal prosecutors at the US Department of Ju=
stice. But it is harder for the US Securities and Exchange Commission, beca=
use the SEC can regulate only securities, and there is disagreement about w=
hich crypto tokens are =E2=80=9Csecurities.=E2=80=9D On the one hand, the S=
EC=C2=A0really=C2=A0wants to bring these cases:
=09It wants to be the regulator in charge of crypto, and cracking down on m=
anipulation and fraud is a key aspect of that.=09These cases =E2=80=94=C2=
=A0market manipulation, insider trading, etc. =E2=80=94=C2=A0tend to be eas=
y cases to win, since the people did bad stuff. If the SEC brings cases aga=
inst crypto lending platforms, arguing that they are doing unregistered sec=
urities offerings, those lending platforms will hire good lawyers and tell =
a sympathetic story about how they are trying to offer a good product that =
people want; a judge might rule that their offering was not a security. (It=
 is easier for the SEC if the lending platform has   already lost its custo=
mers=E2=80=99 money!)=C2=A0If it brings a case=C2=A0against a crypto inside=
r trader, a judge won=E2=80=99t want to throw out the case because=C2=A0the=
 insider trader seems bad, so the judge will be=C2=A0more inclined to rule =
that the relevant token was a security.=09Thus, by going after the worst ca=
ses in crypto, the SEC can expand its jurisdiction without too much objecti=
on.

On the other hand, these cases are awkward:
=09The SEC does have to prove not only the bad conduct (manipulation, insid=
er trading, etc.) and bad intent, but also that the underlying thing was a =
security. Federal prosecutors don=E2=80=99t have that problem; they can jus=
t argue that the conduct was wire fraud.=09If the underlying thing was a se=
curity, then=C2=A0probably=C2=A0it was offered illegally. If you bought som=
e crypto token and pumped up the price and then sold it and the SEC sues yo=
u for market manipulation, you can say =E2=80=9Cwell it wasn=E2=80=99t a se=
curity,=E2=80=9D and the SEC can say =E2=80=9Cyes it was,=E2=80=9D and you =
can say =E2=80=9Cwell the people who issued the security didn=E2=80=99t reg=
ister it with the SEC and offer it legally,=E2=80=9D and the SEC can say =
=E2=80=9Cdoesn=E2=80=99t matter, you still can=E2=80=99t manipulate it,=E2=
=80=9D and you can say things like =E2=80=9Cwell then I was defrauded too, =
since I bought it from them,=E2=80=9D or =E2=80=9Cwhy are you going after m=
e and not them?=E2=80=9D

So we   talked in   October about Avi Eisenberg, who exploited a decentrali=
zed finance protocol called Mango Markets for about $116 million, and then =
bragged about it, saying that =E2=80=9CI believe=C2=A0all of our actions we=
re legal open market actions, using the protocol as designed, even if the d=
evelopment team did not fully anticipate all the consequences of setting pa=
rameters the way they are.=E2=80=9D Federal prosecutors did not agree, and =
he was arrested in December; we   talked about this too. He was charged wit=
h=C2=A0commodities fraud: He traded futures on Mango tokens, crypto futures=
 are plausibly=C2=A0=E2=80=9Ccommodity futures=E2=80=9D under relevant US l=
aw, and manipulating them is straightforwardly a crime. The US Commodity Fu=
tures Trading Commission also  brought a civil case against Eisenberg.
But the futures and tokens that he traded =E2=80=94=C2=A0MNGO, the governan=
ce token of Mango Markets, and related futures on MNGO =E2=80=94=C2=A0are j=
ust obviously=C2=A0securities; MNGO is essentially a share of=C2=A0stock=C2=
=A0in the Mango protocol. Well, that=E2=80=99s what I think, and it=E2=80=
=99s also what the SEC thinks. And so last week the SEC  brought its own ma=
rket manipulation case against Eisenberg:

=E2=80=9CAs we allege, Eisenberg engaged in a manipulative and deceptive sc=
heme to artificially inflate the price of the MNGO token, which was purchas=
ed and sold as a crypto asset security, in order to borrow and then withdra=
w nearly all available assets from Mango Markets, which left the platform a=
t a deficit when the security price returned to its pre-manipulation level,=
=E2=80=9D said David Hirsch, Chief of the Crypto Assets and Cyber Unit. =E2=
=80=9CAs our action shows, the SEC remains committed to rooting out market =
manipulation, regardless of the type of security involved.=E2=80=9D
The SEC=E2=80=99s complaint, filed in federal district court in Manhattan, =
charges Eisenberg with violating anti-fraud and market manipulation provisi=
ons of the securities laws and seeks permanent injunctive relief, a conduct=
-based injunction, disgorgement with prejudgment interest, and civil penalt=
ies.

The  complaint covers the same basic facts as the Justice Department=E2=80=
=99s and CFTC=E2=80=99s cases, but it also has a long analysis of why the M=
ango tokens were securities. This does require the SEC to say, or at least =
hint, that Mango=E2=80=99s developers were also breaking the law:

Mango Offers and Sells MNGO Tokens in Unregistered Transactions.
Between August 9 and 10, 2021, Mango offered and sold 500 million MNGO toke=
ns (5% of the maximum supply), in exchange for consideration in the form of=
 the crypto assets known as USD Coin (=E2=80=9CUSDC=E2=80=9D), to the gener=
al public on its website (https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/303=
34334.286518/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cudG9rZW4ubWFuZ28ubWFya2V0cyku/607f07ceef4b8524a=
319a23cB7a6ccf0c
To publicly promote the offer and sale of MNGO, Mango published, among othe=
r things, a =E2=80=9CLitepaper=E2=80=9D that generally described the terms =
of the offering and certain rights that MNGO token holders would be entitle=
d to. =E2=80=A6
U.S. investors were purportedly ineligible to participate in this MNGO toke=
n sale. However, at least several investors who received MNGO tokens from t=
he initial distribution, including several of Mango Markets=E2=80=99 creato=
rs, resided in the United States at the time.

See, really Eisenberg was a=C2=A0victim=C2=A0of=C2=A0Mango=E2=80=99s=C2=A0f=
raud: They sold him securities without proper disclosure and registration. =
And then he manipulated them.

