   =20
      Oh Elon
   =20
 =20

I was trained as a sell-side public-company mergers-and-acquisitions lawyer=
, and I suppose if there is one most important lesson that I learned in tha=
t training, it was: Make sure you collect your fee. The problem with public=
-company M&A is that, when a merger closes, the target company disappears; =
it becomes a unit of the buyer, and the buyer controls its checking account=
. The target=E2=80=99s advisers =E2=80=94=C2=A0its bankers and, usually, it=
s lawyers =E2=80=94=C2=A0get paid a fee that is contingent on the deal clos=
ing, which means that they get paid at or after the time the deal actually =
closes. Meaning that, technically, the buyer pays their fees. What if he do=
esn=E2=80=99t?
So there=E2=80=99s   that time that Warren Buffett offered to pay $850 per =
share to buy Alleghany Corp., then reduced the price to $848.02 when he rea=
lized how much he=E2=80=99d have to pay for Alleghany=E2=80=99s bankers. Th=
e bankers got paid, but it was awkward, since their fee=C2=A0so directly an=
d publicly reduced the price that shareholders got.
  [1]
=C2=A0Or there=E2=80=99s the=C2=A0time that Carl Icahn made a hostile bid t=
o acquire CVR Energy Inc., which hired bankers to fend him off.=C2=A0The ba=
nkers did=C2=A0not=C2=A0fend him off, which meant that they were entitled t=
o an M&A fee, and he refused to pay it. They  sued and eventually got their=
 fee, but it was not very fun. (He also  sued CVR=E2=80=99s lawyers over th=
e banks=E2=80=99 fees. Disclosure: The CVR bankers and lawyers were Goldman=
 Sachs Group Inc. and Wachtell, Lipton, Rosen & Katz; I worked at both plac=
es.)
Elon Musk closed his deal to buy Twitter Inc. last October, and it was abou=
t as hostile as public-company M&A gets, in that (1) Musk initially approac=
hed Twitter as a hostile bidder, (2) eventually the deal became friendly, i=
n a technical sense (nobody seemed to=C2=A0like=C2=A0each other?), and they=
 signed a merger agreement, but then (3) Musk tried to get out of it by acc=
using Twitter of fraud, and there was a bitter court battle that ended with=
 Musk caving and buying Twitter. Also since buying Twitter Musk has gotten =
rid of 80% of its employees,   refused to pay severance to executives,=C2=
=A0and cut costs by   selling the coffee machines and  not paying rent. So =
I guess what I am saying is that I hope that Twitter=E2=80=99s bankers and =
lawyers got paid out of the wire transfers at closing. Its   expert witness=
es did not, and oops:

Twitter Inc. was sued by a consulting firm that claims it=E2=80=99s owed ar=
ound $2 million for work relating to its lawsuit to force Elon Musk to comp=
lete his buyout of the social-media platform.
Charles River Associates sued Twitter on Thursday in state court in Boston.=
 The firm said it was hired in August to provide expert economic testimony =
to rebut the witness Musk was expected to put on the stand. But Musk revers=
ed himself in October and agreed to move ahead with his $44 billion acquisi=
tion.

Yeah I mean, they were hired to testify against him at trial, and then he d=
idn=E2=80=99t go to trial! Why would he want to pay them?

