<tr>
<td style=3D"border-collapse: collapse; mso-table-lspace: 0pt; mso-table-rs=
pace: 0pt;">
<table class=3D"body-component" width=3D"100%" border=3D"0" cellspacing=3D"=
0" cellpadding=3D"0">
<tr>
<td class=3D"body-component__content" style=3D"border-collapse: collapse; m=
so-table-lspace: 0pt; mso-table-rspace: 0pt; line-height: 150%; padding: 0 =
10px;">
<table class=3D"header" width=3D"100%" border=3D"0" cellspacing=3D"0" cellp=
adding=3D"0">
<tr>
<td class=3D"body-header-container" style=3D"border-collapse: collapse; mso=
-table-lspace: 0pt; mso-table-rspace: 0pt;">
<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Everything is bank fraud</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">You know <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloomber=
gbusiness.com/click/30334334.286518/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGl=
uaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMDItMDMvZ29sZG1hbi1zYWNocy1nb2VzLXRvLXN1cHJlbWUtY2=
91cnQtaGVkZ2UtZnVuZHMtd29uLW9uLWdhbWVzdG9wLWtrcG9lNndzP2NtcGlkPUJCRDAxMjMyM=
19NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90=
ZXJtPTIzMDEyMyZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB40f=
f94b5" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" sty=
le=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width=
: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background=
-color: #ccc;">  my theory</a>: Every bad thing that a public company does =
is=C2=A0<em>also=C2=A0</em>securities fraud. If there is a data breach=C2=
=A0or sexual harassment or animal mistreatment or pollution at a company,=
=C2=A0and the public finds out about it and the stock goes down, then someo=
ne will sue the company, arguing that it defrauded shareholders by leading =
them to believe that there=C2=A0<em>wouldn=E2=80=99t</em> be=C2=A0a data br=
each or sexual harassment or whatever. And this theory is=C2=A0<em>weird</e=
m>, and people sometimes say =E2=80=9Cwait shouldn=E2=80=99t securities fra=
ud be for, like, accounting misstatements, not sexual harassment?=E2=80=9D =
But it is a little hard to articulate a limiting principle. If a company co=
nvinces investors that it is good, but it is in fact bad, then it has defra=
uded them, and badness is not limited to accounting.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Once you have mastered this basic idea, you ca=
n apply it to other laws. For instance, every bad thing that a company does=
 is=C2=A0<em>also=C2=A0</em>bank fraud, if the company has ever borrowed mo=
ney from a bank. The <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/cli=
ck/30334334.286518/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cud3NqLmNvbS9hcnRpY2xlcy9hbWF6b24tZmFjaW5n=
LXF1ZXN0aW9ucy1vdmVyLXdvcmtwbGFjZS1zYWZldHktYWxzby1wcm9iZWQtb24tYmFuay1kZWF=
saW5ncy0xMTY3NDI2MzE2Nj9yZWZsaW5rPWRlc2t0b3B3ZWJzaGFyZV90d2l0dGVy/607f07cee=
f4b8524a319a23cB369adb0f" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" ta=
rget=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; =
border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style=
: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> Wall Street Journal reports</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The U.S. government is looking into whether Am=
azon.com Inc. might have misled lenders about its workplace safety record t=
o obtain credit, using a law stemming from the savings-and-loan crisis in a=
 legal move a lawyer for the company called =E2=80=9Cunprecedented.=E2=80=
=9D</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The Manhattan U.S. Attorney=E2=80=99s Office i=
s conducting an investigation into Amazon under the Financial Institutions =
Reform, Recovery and Enforcement Act, a law that allows civil cases to be b=
rought over wrongdoing that impacts banks. The office has deployed the 1989=
 law at the same time the Labor Department presses a workplace safety inves=
tigation of Amazon that has already led to several citations. =E2=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The U.S. Attorney=E2=80=99s Office in Manhatta=
n issued a subpoena in August to Amazon for information the company might h=
ave shared with financial institutions involved in at least $90 million in =
contracts or agreements with the online retailer in the previous five years=
, specifically information it shared on its injury rates and labor law comp=
liance. =E2=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CIt is difficult to understand how a s=
afety inquiry could plausibly be shoehorned into a Firrea investigation,=E2=
=80=9D Zainab Ahmad, a partner at outside counsel Gibson, Dunn &amp; Crutch=
er LLP, wrote in a letter to government lawyers that is included with court=
 papers.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CFirrea addresses financial fraud, not=
 employee safety,=E2=80=9D Ms. Ahmad added, calling the U.S. Attorney=E2=80=
=99s Office=E2=80=99s legal theory =E2=80=9Cextremely tenuous=E2=80=9D and =
=E2=80=9Cunprecedented.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">It is very easy to understand how a safety inq=
uiry could plausibly be shoehorned into a Firrea investigation!=C2=A0Ahmad =
doesn=E2=80=99t <em>like </em>it, and really neither do=C2=A0I, but I=C2=A0=
<em>understand=C2=A0</em>it.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Amazon has an equity market capitalization jus=
t shy of $1 trillion, tens of billions of dollars per year of cash flow fro=
m operations, A1/AA credit ratings=C2=A0and 5-year credit default swaps tha=
t trade inside of 50 basis points. If you are a bank and you loaned Amazon =
$90 million (!?) in the last five years, you are just fine with that decisi=
on. No bank has become insolvent because it loaned money to Amazon and now =
Amazon is facing =E2=80=9Cseveral citations=E2=80=9D from the Labor Departm=
ent.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But, sure! In its <a href=3D"https://link.mail=
.bloombergbusiness.com/click/30334334.286518/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9Bcm=
NoaXZlcy9lZGdhci9kYXRhLzEwMTg3MjQvMDAwMTE5MzEyNTIwMTc2NTI4L2Q5NDg4NDlkZXgxM=
DEuaHRt/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBe19637c1" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=
=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: =
none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; bo=
rder-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> credit agreement</a>, A=
mazon says that it complies with the law, so if it did not comply with labo=
r law then its credit agreement was not strictly true. And perhaps in the d=
ue diligence for a loan, a bank sent over a questionnaire asking things lik=
e =E2=80=9Care your workplaces safe,=E2=80=9D and probably Amazon answered =
=E2=80=9Cyes=E2=80=9D in some sort of qualified and lawyered way, and if th=
e answer should have been =E2=80=9Cno=E2=80=9D then, right, fraud. Of cours=
e no one at a bank=C2=A0<em>made a credit decision=C2=A0</em>based on that =
questionnaire. It=E2=80=99s not like Jamie Dimon was called in to decide wh=
ether JPMorgan Chase &amp; Co. should lend to Amazon, and he said =E2=80=9C=
hmm, I don=E2=80=99t know, how=E2=80=99s their safety record,=E2=80=9D and =
the analyst who sent the due diligence questionnaire was like =E2=80=9Cwell=
 they say here that it=E2=80=99s good,=E2=80=9D and Dimon said =E2=80=9Cwel=
l okay, if you think we can trust them about that, then let=E2=80=99s lend =
them the money,=E2=80=9D and JPMorgan went ahead on that basis and was shoc=
ked to find out that Amazon=E2=80=99s safety record was not so good. Presum=
ably what happened is that some credit committee made the credit decision b=
y asking =E2=80=9Cwait this is Amazon?=E2=80=9D and the relationship banker=
 was like =E2=80=9Cyep=E2=80=9D and the credit committee was like =E2=80=9C=
sure wave it in=E2=80=9D and nobody discussed worker safety at all. And if =
they did, it was probably along the lines of =E2=80=9Cwell, Amazon is a hug=
e company and a great credit, shame about its spotty worker safety record b=
ut we gotta make this loan.=E2=80=9D</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Oh, I am being a little glib. Sometimes banks =
consider not only the actual credit risk of a financing but also the reputa=
tional risk: Even if you think some major oil company is huge and stable an=
d a great credit, you=E2=80=99ll probably have a contentious committee meet=
ing about lending it money, because there is activist pressure on banks not=
 to lend to oil companies. (And, of course, <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bl=
oombergbusiness.com/click/30334334.286518/aHR0cHM6Ly9jb21wdHJvbGxlci50ZXhhc=
y5nb3YvYWJvdXQvbWVkaWEtY2VudGVyL25ld3MvMjAyMjA4MjQtdGV4YXMtY29tcHRyb2xsZXIt=
Z2xlbm4taGVnYXItYW5ub3VuY2VzLWxpc3Qtb2YtZmluYW5jaWFsLWNvbXBhbmllcy10aGF0LWJ=
veWNvdHQtZW5lcmd5LWNvbXBhbmllcy0xNjYxMjY3ODE1MDk5/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB=
28668fcf" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" =
style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-wi=
dth: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; backgro=
und-color: #ccc;"> pressure the other way</a>.)=C2=A0My impression is that =
lending money to Amazon is not really in this category, but is it possible =
that the deal memo had a paragraph like =E2=80=9CReputational risk: A lot o=
f people don=E2=80=99t like how Amazon treats its workers=E2=80=9D? Is it p=
ossible that the deal memo went on to say =E2=80=9CMitigating factor: Amazo=
n says its workplace safety is good=E2=80=9D? I mean, sure. Would its banks=
 have loaned it the money on the same terms no matter what Amazon said abou=
t its workplace safety? Yes, I think so. But you can understand how the pro=
secutors might be doing the shoehorning.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Elsewhere, and related, here is Patrick McKenz=
ie on =E2=80=9C<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/303=
34334.286518/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYml0c2Fib3V0bW9uZXkuY29tL2FyY2hpdmUva3ljLWFuZC=
1hbWwtYmV5b25kLXRoZS1hY3Jvbnltcy8_cmVmPWJpdHMtYWJvdXQtbW9uZXktbmV3c2xldHRlc=
g/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB2775a94c" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"it=
emscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !=
important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-b=
ottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">KYC and AML: beyond the acrony=
ms</a>=E2=80=9D:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Many, many crimes involve lies, but most lies =
told are not crimes and most lies told are not recorded for forever. We did=
, however, make a special rule for lies told=C2=A0<em>to banks</em>: they=
=E2=80=99re potentially very serious crimes and they will be recorded with =
exacting precision, for years, by one of the institutions in society most c=
apable of keeping accurate records and most findable by agents of the state=
.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This means that if your crime touches money, a=
nd much crime is financially motivated, and you get beyond the threshold of=
 crime which can be done purely offline and in cash, you will at some point=
 attempt to interface with the banking system. And you will lie to the bank=
s, because you need bank accounts, and you could not get accounts if you to=
ld the whole truth.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The government=C2=A0<em>wants you to do this</=
em>. Their first choice would be you not committing crimes, but contingent =
on you choosing to break the law, they=C2=A0<em>prefer you also lie to a ba=
nk</em>.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Same idea with workplace safety violations.</p=
>
